<div class="meta-issue"><a href="/issues/security/view/" >Foreign Policy and Security</a></div>
<h1 class="entry-title">Bridging the Divide in the U.S.-South Korea Alliance</h1>

<div class="col-md-12"><span class="time"><span class="byline"> 
By Michael Fuchs and <a href="/about/staff/lee-haneul/bio/">Haneul Lee</a>
</span>
 <span class="posted-on"> <time class="published" datetime="November 23, 2020 at 9:03 am">November 23, 2020,  9:03 am</time></span></span></div>

<div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-9 col-md-9">
	<div>
		<div class="report-image">
			<img src="https://cdn.americanprogress.org/content/uploads/2020/11/20063049/GettyImages-1228026517.jpg" alt="Bridging the Divide in the U.S.-South Korea Alliance"/>		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="col-xs-10">
		<div class="photo-meta">
			<span>Getty/Jung Yeon-je</span>
			<p class="photo-caption">Visitors hold Korean traditional lanterns at Changdeokgung Palace in Seoul, South Korea, on August 13, 2020.</p>
		</div>
	</div>
</div><!-- image/caption container -->

<div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-3 col-md-3 lfr-accordion">
		<div class="report-acc">
			

			<div id="report-overview">
				<div class="overview-container">
					<ul class="accordion-tabs">
						
						<li class="tab-header-and-content">
							<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="tab-header is-active tab-link"><h4>OVERVIEW<i></i></h4></a>
							<div class="tab-content">
								<p>For the U.S.-South Korea alliance to be most effective, the two countries must strive to understand one another—and progressives must find common ground on key challenges.</p>
							</div>
						</li>

						
																			<li class="tab-header-and-content">
								<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="tab-header tab-link"><h4>PRESS CONTACT<i></i></h4></a>
								<div class="tab-content">
									<aside class="widget widget-bar"><div class="widget-body"><div class="press-contact-element">Sam Hananel</div><div class="press-contact-element"></div><div class="press-contact-element"><a href='shananel' title='americanprogress.org' class='email-link'>&#x202E;g&#8203;r&#8203;o&#8203;.&#8203;s&#8203;s&#8203;e&#8203;r&#8203;g&#8203;o&#8203;r&#8203;p&#8203;n&#8203;a&#8203;c&#8203;i&#8203;r&#8203;e&#8203;m&#8203;a&#8203;&commat;&#8203;l&#8203;e&#8203;n&#8203;a&#8203;n&#8203;a&#8203;h&#8203;s&#x202D;</a></div><div class="press-contact-element"></div></div></aside>								</div>
							</li>
																	</ul>
				</div>
			</div> <!-- report-overview -->
		</div> <!-- report-acc -->
	</div> <!-- xs -->

<div class="col-xs-12">
	<article id="post-493041" class="post-493041 reports type-reports status-publish has-post-thumbnail hentry tag-asia-pacific tag-international tag-national-security issue-security report_type-report person-lee-haneul person-fuchs-michael">
		<div class="entry-content">
										<section class="ccb ccb-chapter" data-chapter-title="Introduction and summary">
						<h2 class="chapter-title ">Introduction and summary</h2>					</section>
		
		
<p>The United States’ alliance with South Korea is one of its most important relationships—not just in Asia but around the world. Yet no alliance is without disagreement, and as the United States and South Korea’s partnership approaches its eighth decade, new geopolitical realities could pose obstacles to its integrity.</p>
                <div class="shortcode newsletter-short col-md-4 gdpr-hide" style="float:right!important; margin-left: 75px;">
                    <h3>Subscribe to <i>InProgress</i></h3>
